## TL;DR:

- The percentage of severely underpowered Regular CS experiments ([definition](#definition-of-'severely-underpowered-regular-csbqrt-experiments')), is on average [60%](https://fburl.com/datainsights/uokpbp5i) for 2024. The team has a H2 2024 [goal](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1c7Mf4ZKT8SGYaleqbohmEE1XKz3JJjjlxxQ7d-GZaE4/edit#bookmark=id.f5b8z11zkfu1) to reduce this to 25% (p80, and 10% p50).   
- Approximatel[y 5% of traffic](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1llDXy1cKsugqokDvrij0rNVI2J9ZnJkGn4Cfubm7y24/edit#bookmark=id.k1oayu1uqpit) is [wasted](https://fburl.com/daiquery/1d0yymwi) (with high variance, up to 18%) on those experiments, leading to preventable iRev loss and experimenter time, wasted in unproductive cycles. It is crucial for experiments, especially in our resource-constrained platform, to be [appropriately sized and run until results stabilize.](https://www.internalfb.com/intern/wiki/Better_Decisions/Standards/Experimentation_Standards/)  
- This project targets to reduce underpowered intent-to-launch experiments to 30%.  As a stretch goal, we aim for 10%, achieving the team’s p50 goal for the metric.  
- We will achieve this by onboarding regular experiments onto the scheduler by estimating [traffic selection bias](https://fb.workplace.com/notes/786181566499010/) and mde, and adding constraints for them as blockers for scheduling.   
- We will also onboard Clustered CS BQRT on the scheduler. This means we will be able to tell if there is cluster degradation due to small or (long) regular experiments running in the same batch with higher priority and open the door to increasing [small experiments limit.](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Imb43o5YzM9sjXE71P633R7XeRdz58iJgHMnRwsaAcQ/edit#heading=h.3tbp6mrwqcs4)   
- We will achieve this by expanding the current estimation capabilities for CSBQRT experiments, and modifying the computational cadence and frequency of [Clustered](https://fb.workplace.com/notes/627235642393604/) CSBQRT to ensure the accuracy of these estimates.

## Proposal Outline

### Onboarding Regular Experiments on Scheduler

#### How

- The current [experiment traffic forecasting](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LZzI4-iJ04iEJ32xkUsN_FHwFzM01YdNXFmihcGkRIc/edit#heading=h.3vcvru4fyjdz) assumes ‘traffic is same week over week’ and simulates the backend assignment. More formally, [**the vector of  #impressions per custom flag changes slowly over time**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LZzI4-iJ04iEJ32xkUsN_FHwFzM01YdNXFmihcGkRIc/edit#heading=h.t8di5wg9o0to) **([evidence](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LZzI4-iJ04iEJ32xkUsN_FHwFzM01YdNXFmihcGkRIc/edit#heading=h.i8gs37tnbil3)-the cosine similarity of such vectors 1 month apart, is 0.9687 ).** It uses that assumption to assume that the snapshot of today’s vector is a good forecast for the next few weeks. Thus the forecast is a simulation of the ‘what would the adunit distribution to experiments be if they were to run today’+ counting.  
- We need 3 parts:   
  1. forecast an adset, requested for each experiment;   
  2. then compute forecasted metrics (power, #adunits, MDE, potentially more) on its basis;   
  3. decide on, compute and enforce constraints for scheduling.  
- To do the first, we rearrange some of the cluster-related computation's timelines, and reuse the current traffic estimator with modifications (it computes adunits as an intermediate step in cs_bqrt_estimator_eligibility_results).  
- For the second, we expand the power calculator.  
- We also will create/reuse a pipeline, computing clustering characteristics the basis of ad-experiment mappings, rather than only live experiments.  
- Finally, we need to enforce the constraints as part of the scheduler.

#### Risks

- Overall need to care when touching cluster-related. Mitigation:bias development towards safety during testing and rollout. [See more](#bookmark=id.bttjfuy1neze)..   
- Forecasted vs observed MDE not matching for some reasons.  Mitigation: planned buffer in [Milestone 1.3: Estimator: #adunits estimates-> power estimates](#milestone-1.3:-estimator:-#adunits-estimates->-power-estimates) and [Milestone 1.4 Power estimator: compare and triangulate estimates and observed mde](#milestone-1.4-power-estimator:-compare-and-triangulate-estimates-and-observed-mde).   
- Need to research data to use for migration to power estimator. Mitigation: as previous point.  
- Experiments may not get traffic due to bad or non-existant forecasts, or because of data blockouts, caused by SEV's, correctness issues, etc. This proposal touches only on the forecast part. Mitigation: can adjust guardrails for regular to have higher quality (lower forecasted MDE) standards than is strictly needed to account for expected # of blockouts.

### **Background**

You can find an overview of our current experiment types and their pros and cons [here](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1virCPI2IOGacb1DMOHK6NaZbkPhESr8WmOnGlW62zRQ/edit#heading=h.gj61wnnsn6kt). We propose to improve the traffic governance for regular experiments by adding power guardrails to them, also making them more predictable. Further, onboarding clustered experiments to the estimator will also ensure their quality further.

### **Goals**

We want to onboard Regular and Clustered CSBQRT's onto the scheduler. Concretely, this means:  
0. The percentage of severely underpowered Regular CS experiments is on average [60%](https://fburl.com/datainsights/uokpbp5i) for 2024. With this project, we aim to reduce this goal to 30% (p80, and 10% as a stretch goal).  
1. Being able to compute the impact of rest of schedule on clusters in terms of traffic selection bias (and auction purity?), and prevent low-quality clusters that are hurt by the rest of the batch, from running.

# High-Level Design

### Current, Ideal, and Target State for this Proposal

In **summary**,here we will move towards the **ideal** state by:

- Adding guardrails for starting regular experiments with ‘intent to launch flag, so we don’t have ones with no power- ([Milestone 1.4](#heading=h.6h5z3hwionmg)).  
- Computing the current clustering guardrails, while knowing about the batch (so they are checked both at cluster creation time, and at batch creation time, to ensure cluster quality).

#### Need to onboard Clustered Experiments in order to onboard Regular

![][image3]

 Here, due to the nature of the priority system, not knowing the adset for a given experiment blocks estimation for anything with lower priority. 

#### Proposed Solution

The estimation flow for CS-BQRT’s can roughly be divided in 2 parts:

- Given candidate experiments of a batch, figure out a forecast probability of assigning a given adunit to an experiment (justified by the claim/observation that adunits are in [equilibrium wrt custom flags](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LZzI4-iJ04iEJ32xkUsN_FHwFzM01YdNXFmihcGkRIc/edit#heading=h.wdne1s81v88t))   
- Given these probabilities, compute metrics on the forecasted traffic for experiments, and put guardrails on those.

So, we are to execute the following sequence of steps:

1. Change clustering timing and computation cadence in order to know which  experiments will be running, with all their settings, determining requested traffic, before the scheduler runs. See details [here](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1JVp9l2Fn6kp2R3u5cJcdsdpuPW07mDeb3M2C3TvY60I/edit#heading=h.bbj74n2krve), supporting multiple options. Tradeoffs are ease of implementation vs supporting longer or shorter planning horizons.  
2. Using this knowledge, modify input experiments to the current traffic estimator to cover clustered and regular experiments to be run in the batch in question (candidates fetch in estimator_utils.py).  
3. Additionally, enhance traffic estimator to compute mde/power, instead of adunits; and make it comparable with post-experiment results.  
4. Create traffic selection bias pipelines to work on not-yet-running experiments (adsets) and forecast batch-aware traffic selection bias. This is a requirement to enable estimation of the impact on clusters by the rest of the batch.  
5. Use calculations from 3 and 4 to stop severely underpowered regular experiments from running  
6. Use calculations from 3 and 4 to detect clusters, most affected by the current batch, and flag/prevent them from running.

## Small Experiments Limit Increase

In addition, as another stretch goal, we will aim to increase the small experiment limit safely, protecting the integrity of clustered experiments. We aim to  produce tooling that would allow us to assess if an increase of small experiment limits to [0.16% of the traffic](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1ixkDdNqKQ4tgBLdohiCtqLmiqYkYyu9MAI0tuR0d-3A/edit), instead of 0.1%, and increasing the total cap of small experiments to e.g. 4%, would affect clusters negatively. This would allow us to easily answer questions like 'can we still get 14 clusters with expected country selection bias \\&lt;0.4 and comparable auction purity?'.  

# Appendix

## Onboarding Experiments on Schedulers - why and how? {#onboarding-experiments-on-schedulers---why-and-how?}

See [\[RFC\] Budget A/B Test Scheduler Roadmap/Vision](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1virCPI2IOGacb1DMOHK6NaZbkPhESr8WmOnGlW62zRQ/edit#heading=h.gj61wnnsn6kt)for more details on the continuum of tradeoffs between traffic quality guarantees between Full BQRT and regular/small CS, and what we can add to the offerings to bridge any remaining gaps.

#### Experiment Health State

Currently, the state of pre-experiment run guardrails are as follows:

- **Cluster experiments have rich guardrails**   
- **Small experiments have some guardrails.**   
- **Regular CS experiments -none and at the bottom of the priority list, thus making it extremely unreliable for them to get the sort of traffic they're asking for.**  
- **In addition, there is currently no capability to compute metrics, similar to the ones clusters enjoy pre- experiment run, or have them use information about the batch. This blocks the possibility to shift around traffic between experiment types, based on the demand.**

The present doc proposes to add such capability and has as stretch goals to make it possible to do it for multiple weeks ahead in a reliable way.  
 In addition, it also provides capability to estimate the impact of experiments, running or in the batch or the clustered experiments, which would help to preserve their launchability and value.

### 

##### Not in scope:

We omit issues about calculation of impression shift,optimal packing, driving away demand, changes in traffic assignment or overall priority of experiment types.  
In addition, we **only gloss over issues like ‘how does the user interact with the result of a particular scheduling-related computation’** and user flows in general.  
At the moment we will postpone regular CS experiments if they fail the guardrails, and notify the users for this. However, this is a subject to change. The topic of ‘corrective actions’, user-flows and similar is still in development and discussed in depth e.g. in  [\[RFC\] Budget A/B Test Scheduler Redesign](https://docs.google.com/document/d/12T_M-GRXyoD-cXvSHkqKqPyqs7njcmdgf_0UpvrBtyg/edit#heading=h.4irzp0sdryjj) [‘bin packing scheduler’ prototype notebook](https://fburl.com/anp/8y6lq8cr).

## Definition of 'Severely Underpowered Regular CSBQRT Experiments' {#definition-of-'severely-underpowered-regular-csbqrt-experiments'}

We rely on the definition from the [**Budget ABTest Detectabilit**](https://fburl.com/unidash/aarq1bp6)y dashboard. At the moment the definition (based on the underlying [query](https://fburl.com/daiquery/qc3saes8)) is:

- Regular experiments with observed SAV AA MDE >1%
